data.chText: （与形容词最高级或与all、every连用，表示强调或概括）想象得到的
data.enText: used with superlatives, and with all and every , to emphasize that sth is the best, worst, etc. that you can imagine, or includes every possible example

data.chText: 从这所房子可以看到所能想象的最壮丽的景色。
data.enText: The house has the most spectacular views imaginable.

data.chText: 他们备有各种能想到的意大利面食。
data.enText: They stock every imaginable type of pasta.

data.chText: 这些科技新产品在30年前几乎是不可想象的。
data.enText: These technological developments were hardly imaginable 30 years ago.

word_means: (与形容词最高级或与all、every连用，表示强调或概括)想象得到的
simple_means.memory_skill: imagin〔e〕想象 + able 可…的 → 可想象的

means: (与形容词最高级或与all、every连用，表示强调或概括)想象得到的

value.def: You use imaginable after a superlative such as 'best' or 'worst' to emphasize that something is extreme in some way.

example.ex: ...their imprisonment under some of the most horrible circumstances imaginable...
example.tran: 他们被关押在可以想象出的最恐怖的环境中

example.ex: He could not disguise that he had had the worst imaginable day for any minister.
example.tran: 他刚刚经历了对于任何部长而言都是最糟糕的一天，这对他来说无法掩饰。

gramarinfo.label: adj-superl n ADJ, adj-superl ADJ n

value.tran: (常与 best，worst 等形容词最高级连用)可想象的,想得到的

value.def: You use imaginable after a word like 'every' or 'all' to emphasize that you are talking about all the possible examples of something. You use imaginable after 'no' to emphasize that something does not have the quality mentioned.

example.ex: ...all of the other imaginable ramifications of this technology...
example.tran: 这项技术可能产生的其他一切后果
父母鼓励孩子参与一切可能的活动。

example.ex: ...a place of no imaginable strategic value.

value.tran: (用于 every，all 之后，表示强调)(一切)可能存在的,(一切)可能发生的;(用于 no 以后)根本

partsOfSpeech.dec: imag 想象 + ine 表抽象名词 → 想象
imagin〔e〕想象 + able 可…的 → 可想象的
imagin〔e〕想象 + ative 有…倾向（性质）的，属于…的 → 富于想象的
